A Cuban Jew Who Sells Products From Japan Succeeds In Miami - tribunedigital-chicagotribune




 



A Cuban Jew Who Sells Products From Japan Succeeds In MiamiAugust 05, 1990|By Derek Reveron, Knight-Ridder Newspapers.MIAMI √¢¬Ä¬î George Feldenkreis arrived in Miami from Havana in 1961 with his pregnant wife, his 1-year-old son, a law degree useless in the United States and $700. He set out to establish an import business. In the process, he tackled a cross-cultural business challenge almost unheard of in those days: He was a Jewish Cuban trying to sell Japanese auto parts to American companies. What`s more, he gambled that an almost non-existent market for Japanese-made auto parts would take off.His long shot paid.Within a year, he founded Carfel, an importer of automobile and motorcycle parts. Next, he founded Supreme International, an importer of guayabera shirts (pleated, embroidered Cuban shirts), now headed by his son, Oscar. Then came Foreign Parts Distributors, followed by Diamond Electronics. Two years ago, Feldenkreis and three business partners started Universal National Bank.Today, Feldenkreis` firms have 250 employees and $50 million in revenue. All the businesses are profitable, he says, and their combined sales are increasing 12 percent a year. His goal is to build a $200 million business.Carfel has provided the financial nourishment for the growth of Feldenkreis` holdings. The company`s success stems from his early cultivation of the Japanese market. Feldenkreis began importing and selling Japanese car parts long before Japanese exports began to dominate the U.S. market. When the export flood began, Carfel was poised for profit.Along with business success has come a rise in social prominence. Feldenkreis has seen to that: ``If you`re working to get better things in life, one of the things you want is recognition from your peers.``He has made the transformation from stranger in a strange land to familiar and influential figure on Miami`s Cuban and Jewish business/social landscapes. He divides his time and money between the two cultures.With a Jewish delegation, he met former President Ronald Reagan in Hollywood, in 1983. With Cuban dignitaries he saw Reagan at the White House in 1985. With Cubans, again, he met the president in Miami in 1986.``He mixes as casually and comfortably as anyone might imagine in both worlds,`` says Lawrence Perl, a business partner in the Universal National Bank venture. ``He has the flavor of his Cuban background, and he is a very proud Jew.``He has built a reputation as a generous contributor to Jewish and Cuban organizations. His wife, Dorita, hosts some of Miami`s grandest and most culturally diverse parties.Friends describe Feldenkreis, 54, as gregarious, smart and methodical.``He takes his time making a decision, but when he makes it, it`s usually the right one,`` says Miami architect Moises Chorowski, who has known Feldenkreis since they both lived in Havana.That`s where Feldenkreis was born. His parents immigrated to Cuba from the Ukraine in 1924. His father was a photographer at Sloppy Joe`s, an internationally popular Havana night spot. He took pictures of celebrities such as Spencer Tracy, Jean Harlow and Mae West.In 1956, while in law school, Feldenkreis suggested that his father strike up a business relationship with Japanese manufacturers. He wasn`t interested. So Feldenkreis and his brother started their own business. They sold products made in Japan such as Formica and auto parts.The business was uprooted after Fidel Castro seized power and Feldenkreis came to Miami.Feldenkreis is rich and charitable. He donates more than 10 percent of his revenue each year to organizations and groups, most of them Jewish or Cuban, he says.Wealthy people who don`t give annoy him.``I have very little respect for them. People who make money and aren`t charitable have a character flaw,`` he said.


